Python is a general-purpose, high-level programming language — meaning it was designed to be readable by humans first and computers second. In this first notebook, we cover where Python came from, why it is worth learning, and how to get it installed and running on your machine.

What is Python.

Python was created by a Dutch programmer named Guido van Rossum. In the late 1980s, Guido wanted a language that was clean, simple, and genuinely enjoyable to use — something that felt closer to plain English than the cryptic symbols of older languages like C. He named it after the British comedy group Monty Python's Flying Circus, not the snake.

Here is how Python evolved over the decades. In 1989, Guido began writing Python over the Christmas holiday. Python 1.0 was released publicly in 1991. Python 2.0 followed in 2000, adding list comprehensions and garbage collection. In 2008, Python 3.0 arrived — a cleaner, more modern version that intentionally broke backward compatibility to fix longstanding design issues. By 2020, Python 2 was officially retired. And from 2023 onward, Python 3.11 through 3.13 have brought significant speed improvements and much better error messages. Today, Python consistently ranks as the most popular programming language in the world — used by beginners learning to code for the first time and by engineers at Google, NASA, and Netflix.

Why Python.

Python is the closest thing programming has to a Swiss Army knife.

Web developers use it to build server-side applications and APIs using frameworks like Django, FastAPI, and Flask. Data scientists use it to explore, clean, and visualize data with libraries like pandas, NumPy, and Matplotlib. Machine learning engineers use it to train AI models with scikit-learn, PyTorch, and TensorFlow. System administrators use it to automate repetitive tasks — renaming files in bulk, scraping websites, scheduling jobs. DevOps engineers use it to write deployment scripts and interact with cloud APIs. And researchers in biology, physics, and astronomy use it for scientific computing.

Python's biggest strength is its ecosystem — tens of thousands of free, installable packages that handle almost anything you need. But there is another reason Python is so approachable: it reads like English. If you wrote out instructions like "for each item in my list, if the item is greater than ten, print it" — that is almost exactly what the Python code looks like. That readability was Guido's primary design goal from day one.

The Zen of Python.

Python has a built-in philosophy document called the Zen of Python, written by Tim Peters. You can read it any time by running import this inside Python.

A few principles stand out for beginners.

Readability counts. Code is read far more often than it is written — by your future self, by teammates, by anyone who maintains it. Python rewards code that is easy to skim and understand.

Simple is better than complex. If you can solve a problem with a straightforward five-line approach or a clever one-liner, the five-line version is almost always the right choice. Cleverness has a cost.

Errors should never pass silently. When something goes wrong, Python should say so loudly — not swallow the error and move on. Hiding bugs makes them much harder to find later.

There should be one — and preferably only one — obvious way to do it. Unlike some languages that offer a dozen equally valid paths to the same result, Python tries to have a single idiomatic way. This is why Python code written by different people tends to look remarkably similar.

Python 3 versus Python 2.

You may occasionally come across old tutorials or Stack Overflow answers that use Python 2. Here is everything you need to know. Python 2 was officially retired on the first of January 2020. It receives no bug fixes, no security patches, nothing. The two versions are not fully compatible — Python 2 code will often fail to run in Python 3.

The most visible difference is the print statement. In Python 2, print was a statement with no parentheses. In Python 3, print is a function and parentheses are required. If you find a tutorial using print without parentheses, it is outdated. Always use Python 3.

Installing Python.

Getting Python on your machine depends on your operating system.

On macOS, one thing worth knowing first — macOS ships with an old version of Python that the system uses internally. Do not rely on it for your own projects. Instead, use Homebrew, which is a free package manager for macOS. Once Homebrew is installed, you run brew install python, then verify with python3 --version.

On Windows, go to python.org, download the latest Python 3 installer, and run it. One critical step — make sure you tick the box that says "Add Python to PATH" before clicking install. Without that, your terminal will not be able to find Python. Verify the install by opening Command Prompt and running python --version.

On Linux, if you are on Ubuntu or Debian, a single apt install command gets you Python 3, pip, and venv all at once. Most modern systems already have Python 3 — this ensures you have the tools you need alongside it.

Virtual Environments.

A virtual environment is an isolated copy of Python that belongs to one specific project. Think of it like giving each project its own separate room with its own set of tools. The hammer in Room A stays in Room A and never clashes with the saw in Room B.

Without virtual environments, every package you install goes into one global pile. Eventually, Project A needs version 2.28 of a library and Project B needs version 2.31, and they cannot both win. Virtual environments solve this completely.

To create a virtual environment, you run python3 -m venv venv in your project folder. This creates a folder called venv. To activate it on Mac or Linux, you source the activate script inside that folder. On Windows, there is an equivalent activate script. Once it is active, your terminal shows the environment name in brackets at the start of the prompt. Every package you install from that point on stays inside this environment — your global Python is untouched. To step back out, you simply run deactivate.

One important convention — always add your venv folder to your dot-gitignore file. You never commit the environment itself to version control. Only the list of packages needed to recreate it.

pip — Installing Packages.

pip is Python's package installer. It connects to the Python Package Index — a public repository of over five hundred thousand free packages — and downloads whatever you need.

You install a single package by name. You can pin it to a specific version using double equals followed by the version number. You can install several packages in one command by listing them together. Running pip freeze shows everything currently installed in the active environment. Saving that output to a file called requirements.txt is the standard convention — that file is what you commit to version control. Anyone who clones your project runs pip install with the requirements file and gets an identical environment.

Running Python — Three Ways.

There are three main ways to run Python code, and each suits a different situation.

The first is the REPL, which stands for Read Eval Print Loop. It is an interactive prompt where you type one line of Python, hit enter, and immediately see the result. You start it by running python3 in your terminal. You type an expression, Python evaluates it and prints the result, and waits for the next input. It is perfect for quick experiments. Type exit to quit.

The second way is a dot-py script. You write your code in a file ending in .py and run it from the terminal using python3 followed by the filename. This is how real Python programs are shipped and run in production.

The third way is a Jupyter notebook — exactly what you are reading right now. Notebooks mix runnable code cells with written explanation. You run code in small chunks, see output inline, and write notes alongside the code. It is the dominant tool in data science and education. You install it with pip install jupyter and launch it with jupyter notebook, which opens a browser interface where you can create and run notebooks.

How Python Runs Your Code.

When you run a Python file, more happens behind the scenes than you might expect. The standard Python interpreter — called CPython — takes your source code through several distinct stages before a single instruction executes.

The first stage is your source code itself. This is the dot-py file you write — plain text that a human can read and understand.

The second stage is the parser. The parser first breaks your text into individual tokens, the way a sentence is broken into words. It then builds something called an Abstract Syntax Tree, or AST — a structured tree that represents what your program means, not just how it is spelled. Think of it as the interpreter building a grammatical model of your code.

The third stage is the compiler. The compiler walks that tree and emits bytecode — a compact stream of low-level instructions. These instructions are saved to a folder called pycache as dot-pyc files. The key point about bytecode is that it is platform-independent. The same bytecode file can run on any machine with the same Python version — the compiler only needs to run once per file, as long as the source has not changed.

The fourth and final stage is the Python Virtual Machine, or PVM. This is a tight loop that fetches each bytecode instruction, decodes it, and executes it. This is the only stage where real computation actually happens.

The reason Python caches bytecode is performance. On subsequent runs of an unchanged file, Python skips the parsing and compilation steps entirely and jumps straight to running the cached bytecode through the PVM.

Hello, World.

By tradition, the first program anyone writes in a new language prints the words "Hello, World!" to the screen. In Python, that is a single line — print with your message inside parentheses and quotes.

From there, you can call print multiple times to output several lines at once, each on its own line. You can use f-strings to build messages dynamically — by putting an f before the opening quote, you can embed variable values directly inside a string using curly braces. And print works just as naturally with numbers and arithmetic expressions — you pass the expression directly and Python evaluates and prints the result. Division always returns a decimal in Python 3, and the double asterisk is the exponentiation operator.

